(every 6-8 weeks) to remove split ends and prevent further damage.\n* **Hydration:** Drink plenty of water to keep your hair and scalp hydrated from within.\n* **Minimize Manipulation:** Avoid excessive brushing or combing, especially when dry. Use a wide-tooth comb on wet hair.\n\n**3. Lifestyle Adjustments:**\n\n* **Sleep:** Aim for at least 7-8 hours of sleep per night, going to bed before midnight whenever possible. Sleep deprivation can negatively impact hair health.\n* **Stress Management:** High stress levels can exacerbate hair loss. Incorporate stress-reducing activities like yoga, meditation, or spending time in nature.\n* **Diet:** A balanced diet rich in protein, iron, and vitamins is crucial for healthy'),
(52, 'janu@gmail.com', 'Wavy Hair', 'Thick', 'Frizzy hair', 'Sensitive', 'Fungal', 'More than 4 days', 'I have psoriasis', 'Surgery or heavy medication', 'PCOS', 'Have difficulty falling asleep', 'High', 'Never', 'Both', 'Improve Hair Quality', 'Low by evening night', 'Cardiovascular disorders', 'Based on your answers, you have wavy, thick, frizzy hair, a sensitive scalp prone to fungal infections and psoriasis, and are experiencing hair issues potentially linked to PCOS, medication, and cardiovascular disorders.  Let\'s address this holistically.\n\n**Addressing Hair Concerns:**\n\n* **Frizzy, Wavy Hair:**  Thick, wavy hair is prone to frizz.  Prioritize moisturizing products. Look for shampoos and conditioners containing humectants (like glycerin or hyaluronic acid) to draw moisture into the hair, and emollients (like shea butter or coconut oil) to seal it in.  Avoid sulfates and silicones which can strip your hair and contribute to frizz.  Consider a leave-in conditioner or a curl cream to define waves and reduce frizz.  Air drying is generally gentler than heat styling, but if you must use heat, always use a heat protectant spray.\n\n* **Sensitive Scalp & Fungal Infections/Psoriasis:**  Your sensitive scalp, coupled with fungal infections and psoriasis, requires gentle, targeted care.  Avoid harsh shampoos and conditioners with fragrances or strong detergents. Look for products specifically formulated for sensitive scalps and those with anti-fungal and anti-inflammatory properties (e.g., shampoos containing ketoconazole, salicylic acid, or coal tar).  Consult a dermatologist or trichologist for diagnosis and treatment of psoriasis and fungal infections; they can prescribe more potent medications if needed.  Avoid scratching your scalp to prevent further irritation and infection.\n\n* **PCOS & Medication Side Effects:** PCOS can significantly impact hair health, often leading to hair thinning or loss.  Similarly, surgery and medication can also contribute to hair changes.  It\'s crucial to discuss these concerns with your doctor. They may recommend blood tests to assess hormone levels and suggest appropriate management strategies for PCOS. They can also advise you on whether your medication is contributing to hair problems.\n\n* **Stress & Sleep:** Your reported difficulty sleeping and high stress levels can negatively affect your hair.  Stress hormones can disrupt the hair growth cycle. Prioritize stress management techniques like yoga, meditation, or spending time in nature. Aim for 7-8 hours of quality sleep per night.  Establish a relaxing bedtime routine to improve your sleep quality.\n\n* **Cardiovascular Disorders:**  Certain cardiovascular medications can have side effects that affect hair.  Discuss any hair changes with your cardiologist to rule out medication-related causes and explore'),
(53, 'janu@gmail.com', 'Curly Hair', 'Normal', 'Frizzy hair', 'Sensitive', 'Redness', 'More than 4 days', 'Yes,I have dandruff', 'Heavy weight loss on heavy weight gain', 'Others hormonal issues', 'Falling asleep post midnight', 'High', '1 month before', 'Both', 'Improve Hair Quality', 'Low by evening night', 'Cardiovascular disorders', 'Based on your responses, it\'s clear you\'re experiencing several factors impacting your curly hair, including frizz, dandruff, and potential hormonal imbalances. Let\'s address these concerns individually:\n\n**1. Frizz and Curly Hair:**\n\n* **Hydration is Key:** Curly hair is naturally drier than straight hair because the curl pattern prevents sebum (natural oil) from traveling down the hair shaft.  Prioritize deep conditioning treatments at least once a week. Look for products containing humectants (like glycerin or hyaluronic acid) to draw moisture into the hair, and emollients (like shea butter or coconut oil) to seal it in.  Avoid sulfates and silicones, which can strip hair of its natural oils.\n* **The Right Products:** Use a curl-defining cream or gel to help define your curls and reduce frizz. Apply these products while your hair is still damp, using the \"scrunching\" method to encourage curl formation.  Consider a leave-in conditioner for extra moisture.\n* **Gentle Handling:** Avoid harsh brushing or combing, especially when your hair is dry. Detangle gently with a wide-tooth comb while your hair is wet and conditioned.\n* **Protective Styles:** Consider protective styles like braids or twists to minimize manipulation and reduce frizz.\n\n**2. Dandruff and Sensitive Scalp:**\n\n* **Gentle Cleansing:** Use a mild, sulfate-free shampoo specifically formulated for dandruff and sensitive scalps. Look for ingredients like pyrithione zinc, selenium sulfide, or ketoconazole.  Avoid harsh scrubbing.\n* **Scalp Massage:** Gently massage your scalp during shampooing to stimulate blood flow and remove dead skin cells.\n* **Natural Remedies (with caution):** Some people find relief from dandruff with natural remedies like tea tree oil or apple cider vinegar diluted in water. However, always do a patch test first to check for any allergic reactions, especially given your sensitive scalp.  If redness persists or worsens, discontinue use.\n\n**3. Hormonal Imbalances and Hair Loss:**\n\nYour responses suggest potential hormonal fluctuations due to weight changes and other hormonal issues.  These can significantly impact hair health.\n\n* **Consult a Doctor:**  The information you provided points to potential underlying health concerns (weight fluctuations, hormonal issues, cardiovascular disorders). It\'s crucial to consult a doctor or dermatologist to rule out any medical conditions contributing to your hair loss and scalp issues.  They can perform tests'),
(54, 'janu@gmail.com', 'Curly Hair', 'Normal', 'Frizzy hair', 'Sensitive', 'Redness', 'More than 4 days', 'Yes,I have dandruff', 'Heavy weight loss on heavy weight gain', 'Others hormonal issues', 'Falling asleep post midnight', 'High', '1 month before', 'Both', 'Improve Hair Quality', 'Low by evening night', 'Cardiovascular disorders', 'Based on your responses, you have curly, frizzy hair prone to dandruff and redness, likely due to a combination of factors including hormonal changes, stress (late nights), and potentially underlying health conditions.  Let\'s address this holistically:\n\n**Addressing Frizz and Curl Definition:**\n\n* **Hydration is Key:** Curly hair is naturally drier than straight hair.  Use a moisturizing shampoo and conditioner specifically designed for curly hair. Look for ingredients like shea butter, coconut oil, glycerin, and hyaluronic acid. Avoid sulfates and silicones, which can strip your hair of its natural oils.\n* **Deep Conditioning:** Incorporate a deep conditioning treatment once a week or as needed. This will help replenish moisture and improve elasticity, reducing frizz.\n* **Leave-in Conditioner:** A leave-in conditioner will provide extra hydration and help detangle your curls, preventing breakage.\n* **Curl Cream or Gel:** Use a curl cream or gel to define your curls and prevent frizz. Apply it while your hair is still damp, scrunching upwards to encourage curl formation.  Experiment with different products to find what works best for your hair type.\n* **Microfiber Towel or T-shirt:** Avoid rubbing your hair with a regular towel, as this can cause frizz. Instead, use a microfiber towel or a soft t-shirt to gently squeeze out excess water.\n* **Protective Styling:** Consider protective styles like braids or twists to minimize manipulation and reduce frizz.\n\n**Managing Dandruff and Scalp Sensitivity:**\n\n* **Gentle Shampoo:** Use a gentle, anti-dandruff shampoo containing ingredients like pyrithione zinc, selenium sulfide, or ketoconazole.  Avoid harsh shampoos that can irritate your sensitive scalp.\n* **Scalp Massage:** Gently massage your scalp while shampooing to stimulate blood flow and remove dead skin cells.\n* **Cool Water Rinse:** Rinse your hair with cool water to close the hair cuticles and reduce frizz.\n* **Identify Triggers:** Keep a journal to track potential triggers for your dandruff and scalp irritation, such as certain hair products, stress, or changes in diet.\n\n**Addressing Hormonal Imbalances and Stress:**\n\n* **Consult a Doctor:**  Given your history of hormonal issues, significant weight fluctuations, and cardiovascular disorders, it\'s crucial to consult your doctor or a dermatologist.  They can help determine if your hair issues are linked to an underlying medical condition requiring treatment.  Hair loss'),
(55, 'user@gmail.com', 'Curly Hair', 'Thick', 'None', 'Dry', 'Redness', '2-3 days', 'I have psoriasis', 'Illness like Dengue typhoid,covid,', 'Thyroid', 'Disturbed sleep, I wake up atleast once a night', 'Low', 'Never', 'Both', 'Regrow Hair', 'Very low in the afternoon', 'Blood pressure', 'It sounds like you\'re dealing with a few challenges related to your thick, curly hair and overall health. Let\'s address them individually:\n\n**Hair Concerns:**\n\n* **Dry, Curly Hair:**  Thick, curly hair is naturally prone to dryness because the natural oils from your scalp have difficulty traveling down the length of each curl.  This is exacerbated by your reported dryness.  Prioritize moisturizing products. Look for shampoos and conditioners specifically designed for dry, curly hair.  These often contain humectants (like glycerin or hyaluronic acid) to attract and retain moisture, and emollients (like shea butter or coconut oil) to soften and smooth the hair.  Avoid sulfates and silicones, which can strip your hair of its natural oils. Consider a deep conditioning treatment once a week or as needed.\n\n* **Scalp Redness and Psoriasis:** The scalp redness suggests your psoriasis may be affecting your hair and scalp. This requires a gentle approach.  Avoid harsh shampoos and styling products that can irritate your scalp. Look for shampoos containing ingredients like salicylic acid, coal tar, or ketoconazole, which can help manage psoriasis symptoms.  However, *always consult your dermatologist* before using any new products on your scalp, especially if you have psoriasis. They can recommend specific treatments and monitor your progress.\n\n* **Hair Regrowth:** Your mention of wanting to regrow hair, combined with your history of illness (Dengue, typhoid, COVID, and thyroid issues), suggests potential hair loss.  Stress, illness, and thyroid imbalances are all known contributors to hair shedding.  Addressing the underlying health conditions is crucial for hair regrowth.  Once your health improves, your hair growth should typically return to normal.  In the meantime, focus on maintaining a healthy scalp and minimizing hair breakage.\n\n**Lifestyle and Health Recommendations:**\n\n* **Sleep:**  Disturbed sleep significantly impacts overall health, including hair health. Aim for 7-8 hours of quality sleep per night.  Establish a relaxing bedtime routine to promote better sleep.\n\n* **Diet:**  A balanced diet rich in protein, iron, and vitamins (especially biotin and Vitamin D) is essential for healthy hair growth.  Your low energy levels might indicate nutritional deficiencies; consult a doctor or registered dietitian for a personalized dietary assessment.\n\n* **Stress Management:**  Stress exacerbates many health conditions, including hair loss and psoriasis.  Explore stress-reducing techniques like'),
